04533nam a22006375i 9781787442481DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874424817 a10.1515/97817874424812doi  a(DE-B1597)675919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0150002bisacsh04a781.62/9639571 aKafumbe, Damascus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTuning the Kingdom :bKawuugulu Musical Performance, Politics, and Storytelling in Buganda /cDamascus Kafumbe.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2018] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (180 p.) :b25 colour, 20 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEastman/Rochester Studies Ethnomusicology ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Translation, Transliteration, and Orthography -- tNote on the Musical Examples -- tPreface: A Kingdom in and out of Tune -- tIntroduction: Kawuugulu Musical Performance, Politics, and Storytelling -- t1 The Kawuugulu Clan-Royal Music and Dance Ensemble -- t2 Kawuugulu and Intra-Clan Politics -- t3 Kawuugulu and Royal Politics -- t4 Kawuugulu and Inter-Clan Politics -- t5 Conclusion: A Performative Constitution -- tAppendix A: Glossary -- tAppendix B: Author Interviews -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines how the Kawuugulu Clan-Royal Musical Ensemble uses musical performance and storytelling to manage, structure, model, and legitimize power relations among the Baganda people of south-central Uganda.Tuning the Kingdom draws on oral and written accounts, archival research, and musical analysis to examine how the Kawuugulu Clan-Royal Musical Ensemble of the Kingdom of Buganda (arguably the kingdom's oldest and longest-surviving performance ensemble) has historically managed, structured, modeled, and legitimized power relations among the Baganda people of south-central Uganda. Damascus Kafumbe argues that the ensemble sustains a complex sociopolitical hierarchy, interweaving and maintaining a delicate balance between kin and clan ties and royal prerogatives through musical performance and storytelling that integrates human and nonhuman stories. He describes this phenomenonas "tuning the kingdom," and he compares it to the process of tensioning or stretching Kiganda drums, which are always moving in and out of tune. Even as Kawuugulu continues to adapt to the rapidly changing world around it, Tuning the Kingdom documents how Kawuugulu has historically articulated and embodied principles of the three inextricably related domains that serve as the backbone of Kiganda politics: kinship, clanship, and kingship.Damascus Kafumbe is Assistant Professor of Music at Middlebury College.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic and identity politicszUgandazBuganda. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszUgandazBuganda. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh  aBaganda people.  aKawuugulu Clan-Royal Musical Ensemble.  acultural heritage.  amusical analysis.  amusical performance.  apower relations.  asouth-central Uganda.  astorytelling.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787442481?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787442481423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787442481/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles